{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_011K77Q1Nc8EiPZnCgrdVKHN","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Story file created. Here is the summary:\n\n**Story 11-3: State Reconciliation on Session Start** has been written to `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/11-3-state-reconciliation-on-session-start.md`.\n\n**Key details:**\n- 12 acceptance criteria (11 tagged `cli-verifiable`, 1 tagged `integration-required` — AC12 about manual YAML edits during session breaks)\n- 6 tasks covering implementation, wiring, exports, tests, and regression verification\n- Reuses existing infrastructure: `generateSprintStatusYaml()`, `parseStoryRetriesRecord()`, `parseFlaggedStoriesList()`, `parseStoryKey()`, `writeStateAtomic()`\n- Dependencies on 11-1 (done) and 11-2 (done) — no blockers\n\n## Session Issues\n\n**Problems encountered:**\n- None.\n\n**Workarounds applied:**\n- The epic definition in `epics-architecture-v3.md` had only 1 AC for story 11-3 (the minimum \"Given/When/Then\" from the epic breakdown). The story was expanded to 12 ACs by examining the technical notes in the original stub file, the implementation of stories 11-1 and 11-2, and the actual codebase (`state.ts`, `migration.ts`, `retry-state.ts`, `run.ts`, `validator.ts`).\n\n**Risks identified:**\n- AC5 (epic consistency validation) assumes story keys always follow the `N-M-slug` pattern. Keys that don't match (e.g., `TD-1-slug` from the planned epic-TD in story 14-1) would need the `parseStoryKey()` function updated. Currently `parseStoryKey()` returns `[Infinity, Infinity]` for non-matching keys, which would create an `epic-Infinity` entry. The implementation should handle this edge case.\n- The orphan file deletion (ACs 3-4) is a one-way operation. If `reconcileState()` deletes `.story_retries` but then the atomic state write fails, the data is lost. The implementation should delete files AFTER successful state write.\n- `writeStateAtomic()` already calls `writeSprintStatusYaml()` as a side-effect, so calling `reconcileState()` which also regenerates YAML and then writes state will cause double YAML generation. Not harmful, just wasteful. The implementation could skip explicit YAML regeneration since `writeStateAtomic()` handles it.\n\n**Observations:**\n- `retry-state.ts` already has `@deprecated` comments saying \"will be removed in story 11-3\" for the legacy path helpers (`retriesPath`, `flaggedPath`). This story should clean those up or at least note it. I did not add an AC for this since the epic definition doesn't mention it and it's a minor cleanup — but the dev agent should be aware.\n- `run.ts` still reads `ralph/.flagged_stories` directly (line 93-101) to pass to the prompt generator, bypassing the sprint-state.json `flagged` field. This is a consumer that story 11-1 missed migrating. `reconcileState()` will delete the file, which would break this code path. The implementation must update `run.ts` to read flagged stories from `state.flagged` instead."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a5302f4312ec68412 (use SendMessage with to: 'a5302f4312ec68412' to continue this agent)\n<usage>total_tokens: 52413\ntool_uses: 19\nduration_ms: 125246</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"01503c00-15e6-46f1-b837-b4628ff69656","uuid":"3eadb4b5-fdac-4597-8656-6d0392a3b5f5","timestamp":"2026-03-24T11:34:34.531Z","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Run /create-story for story 11-3-state-reconciliation-on-session-start. The sprint-status.yaml is at _bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/sprint-status.yaml. Auto-discover the next backlog story and create it. For each AC, append `<!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->` or `<!-- verification: integration-required -->` based on whether the AC can be verified by running CLI commands in a subprocess. ACs referencing workflows, sprint planning, user sessions, or external system interactions should be tagged as integration-required. Do NOT ask the user any questions — proceed autonomously. Do NOT run git commit. Do NOT run git add. Do NOT modify sprint-status.yaml.\n\nMANDATORY — End your response with a `## Session Issues` section listing:\n- Problems encountered (errors, ambiguities in epic definition, missing context)\n- Workarounds applied (anything you did that felt hacky or suboptimal)\n- Risks identified (ACs that seem untestable, unclear requirements, missing dependencies)\n- Observations (anything surprising or noteworthy about this story)\nIf nothing to report, write `## Session Issues\\n\\nNone.`","agentId":"a5302f4312ec68412","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Story file created. Here is the summary:\n\n**Story 11-3: State Reconciliation on Session Start** has been written to `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/11-3-state-reconciliation-on-session-start.md`.\n\n**Key details:**\n- 12 acceptance criteria (11 tagged `cli-verifiable`, 1 tagged `integration-required` — AC12 about manual YAML edits during session breaks)\n- 6 tasks covering implementation, wiring, exports, tests, and regression verification\n- Reuses existing infrastructure: `generateSprintStatusYaml()`, `parseStoryRetriesRecord()`, `parseFlaggedStoriesList()`, `parseStoryKey()`, `writeStateAtomic()`\n- Dependencies on 11-1 (done) and 11-2 (done) — no blockers\n\n## Session Issues\n\n**Problems encountered:**\n- None.\n\n**Workarounds applied:**\n- The epic definition in `epics-architecture-v3.md` had only 1 AC for story 11-3 (the minimum \"Given/When/Then\" from the epic breakdown). The story was expanded to 12 ACs by examining the technical notes in the original stub file, the implementation of stories 11-1 and 11-2, and the actual codebase (`state.ts`, `migration.ts`, `retry-state.ts`, `run.ts`, `validator.ts`).\n\n**Risks identified:**\n- AC5 (epic consistency validation) assumes story keys always follow the `N-M-slug` pattern. Keys that don't match (e.g., `TD-1-slug` from the planned epic-TD in story 14-1) would need the `parseStoryKey()` function updated. Currently `parseStoryKey()` returns `[Infinity, Infinity]` for non-matching keys, which would create an `epic-Infinity` entry. The implementation should handle this edge case.\n- The orphan file deletion (ACs 3-4) is a one-way operation. If `reconcileState()` deletes `.story_retries` but then the atomic state write fails, the data is lost. The implementation should delete files AFTER successful state write.\n- `writeStateAtomic()` already calls `writeSprintStatusYaml()` as a side-effect, so calling `reconcileState()` which also regenerates YAML and then writes state will cause double YAML generation. Not harmful, just wasteful. The implementation could skip explicit YAML regeneration since `writeStateAtomic()` handles it.\n\n**Observations:**\n- `retry-state.ts` already has `@deprecated` comments saying \"will be removed in story 11-3\" for the legacy path helpers (`retriesPath`, `flaggedPath`). This story should clean those up or at least note it. I did not add an AC for this since the epic definition doesn't mention it and it's a minor cleanup — but the dev agent should be aware.\n- `run.ts` still reads `ralph/.flagged_stories` directly (line 93-101) to pass to the prompt generator, bypassing the sprint-state.json `flagged` field. This is a consumer that story 11-1 missed migrating. `reconcileState()` will delete the file, which would break this code path. The implementation must update `run.ts` to read flagged stories from `state.flagged` instead."}],"totalDurationMs":125246,"totalTokens":52413,"totalToolUseCount":19,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3046,"cache_read_input_tokens":48560,"output_tokens":806,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":3046},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}}}
