{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_0184tJvxCPux1RS3fH2NtyBW","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Here is the review summary.\n\n---\n\n**Code Review: Story 11-3 — State Reconciliation on Session Start**\n\n**Files reviewed:**\n- `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/src/modules/sprint/state.ts` (reconcileState implementation)\n- `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/src/commands/run.ts` (integration point)\n- `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/src/modules/sprint/index.ts` (re-export)\n- `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/src/modules/sprint/__tests__/reconciliation.test.ts` (test file)\n- `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/src/commands/__tests__/run.test.ts` (run tests)\n\n**Issues found and fixed:**\n\n1. **HIGH: `reconcileState()` deletes `.flagged_stories` before `run.ts` reads it for prompt generation.** `run.ts` called `reconcileState()` at step 2b which merges and deletes `.flagged_stories`. Then at step 5, it tried to read `.flagged_stories` to pass flagged stories to the Ralph prompt — the file was always gone. Fixed: `run.ts` now reads `state.flagged` from `sprint-state.json` via `getSprintState()` instead of the orphan file.\n\n2. **MEDIUM: Double YAML write when state changed.** `reconcileState()` called `writeSprintStatusYaml(state)` unconditionally, then called `writeStateAtomic(state)` when `changed=true` — which internally calls `writeSprintStatusYaml` again. Fixed: restructured to call `writeSprintStatusYaml` only in the `else` branch (no state change), since `writeStateAtomic` already handles it.\n\n3. **MEDIUM: Missing defensive access on `flagged` field.** The new `getSprintState()` call in `run.ts` accessed `.data.flagged.length` without optional chaining. Callers that mock `getSprintState` with partial data (as the run tests do) would crash. Fixed: changed to `.data.flagged?.length`.\n\n4. **MEDIUM: Run test \"reads flagged stories file when present\" tested deleted behavior.** The test wrote a `.flagged_stories` file and expected `run.ts` to read it directly. After the fix, `run.ts` reads from `sprint-state.json`. Updated the test to provide flagged stories via `getSprintStateMock` instead.\n\n**Results after fixes:**\n- All 3447 tests pass (0 regressions)\n- No new type errors (all TS errors are pre-existing in `verify-env.test.ts` and `bridge.test.ts`)\n- Coverage: 96.82% overall, all 129 files above 80% per-file floor\n- Story status updated to `verifying`\n\n## Session Issues\n\n**Bugs found and fixed:**\n- HIGH: `run.ts` reads `.flagged_stories` file after `reconcileState()` deletes it — flagged stories never passed to Ralph prompt\n- MEDIUM: Double YAML write on state change in `reconcileState()` — wasteful I/O\n- MEDIUM: Missing optional chaining on `flagged` field access — crash with partial mock data\n- MEDIUM: Run test asserted on deleted behavior (reading orphan file directly)\n\n**Code quality issues found but NOT fixed (LOW priority):**\n- `parseStoryKey` is a private function used in both `generateSprintStatusYaml` and `reconcileState` but not exported. If other modules need it, it should be promoted to a shared utility.\n- `run.ts` line 76 `sprintStatusPath` is computed from the filesystem path but only used for the prompt template string — slightly misleading placement after a \"Read sprint status\" comment.\n- The `as` type casts in `reconcileState()` (lines 438, 463, 501) to mutate readonly fields are a code smell. A cleaner approach would be to build a mutable intermediate object and cast to `SprintState` at the end.\n\n**Coverage gaps:**\n- No test for the scenario where `writeStateAtomic` fails during reconciliation (the `fail()` return path at line 510).\n- No integration test verifying that `run.ts` properly passes flagged stories from `sprint-state.json` to the Ralph prompt (the run test uses mocks end-to-end).\n- No test for `reconcileState()` when `getSprintState()` itself fails (returns `fail()`).\n\n**Architecture concerns:**\n- `reconcileState()` calls `getSprintState()` which may trigger `migrateV1ToV2()` which calls `writeStateAtomic()`. Then `reconcileState()` may call `writeStateAtomic()` again. This is two atomic writes in quick succession during migration. Not harmful but worth noting.\n- The `run.ts` now calls `getSprintState()` twice in sequence (once for flagged stories at step 5, once for renderer at step 7). Could be consolidated into a single call.\n\n**Items sent back for re-development:** None."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a53dde4928bb9053b (use SendMessage with to: 'a53dde4928bb9053b' to continue this agent)\n<usage>total_tokens: 65142\ntool_uses: 38\nduration_ms: 266398</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"01503c00-15e6-46f1-b837-b4628ff69656","uuid":"7656d614-a6fb-43c3-ba40-81383bda0dcb","timestamp":"2026-03-24T11:50:34.562Z","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Run /bmad-code-review for the story at _bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/11-3-state-reconciliation-on-session-start.md — perform adversarial review, fix all HIGH and MEDIUM issues found. After fixing, run `codeharness coverage --min-file 80` and ensure all files pass the per-file floor and the overall 90% target. Update the story status to `verifying` when all issues are fixed and coverage passes. Do NOT ask the user any questions — proceed autonomously. Do NOT run git commit. Do NOT run git add. Do NOT modify sprint-status.yaml.\n\nMANDATORY — End your response with a `## Session Issues` section listing:\n- Bugs found and their severity (HIGH/MEDIUM/LOW with brief description)\n- Code quality issues found but NOT fixed (LOW priority items, tech debt)\n- Coverage gaps (files below floor, untested edge cases, areas needing integration tests)\n- Architecture concerns (patterns that don't fit, coupling issues, missing abstractions)\n- Items sent back for re-development (what failed and why)\nIf nothing to report, write `## Session Issues\\n\\nNone.`